about those taverns.

00:38:42.700 --> 00:38:45.130
"In some of the taverns,
slaves sleep on the floor

00:38:45.130 --> 00:38:46.570
of the dining room,
which the master,

00:38:46.570 --> 00:38:49.380
for obvious reasons,
ought to forbid.

00:38:49.380 --> 00:38:53.510
They, [the slaves] have an uncommon
desire for spirituous liquors."

00:38:53.510 --> 00:38:55.720
You know, you see the
racism in that, you know.

00:38:55.720 --> 00:38:57.450
Black people drank too much.

00:38:57.450 --> 00:39:00.190
Okay, now we're going to look
though at what black people thought

00:39:00.190 --> 00:39:01.670
about white people, and we're going

00:39:01.670 --> 00:39:04.570
to see what Josiah
Henson said -- same place.

00:39:04.570 --> 00:39:07.010
This is the same place.

00:39:07.010 --> 00:39:08.310
"My master's habits were

00:39:08.310 --> 00:39:10.960
such as were common enough
among the dissipated planters

00:39:10.960 --> 00:39:13.800
of the neighborhood, and one
of their frequent practices was

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:16.810
to assemble on Saturday or
Sunday which were their holidays,

00:39:16.810 --> 00:39:20.130
and gamble, run horses or fight
gamecocks, discuss politics,

00:39:20.130 --> 00:39:24.960
and drink whiskey and brandy
and water all day long.

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:27.810
Perfectly aware that they would not
be able to find their own way home

00:39:27.810 --> 00:39:30.450
at night, each one ordered
his body servant to come

00:39:30.450 --> 00:39:32.460
after him and help him home.

00:39:32.460 --> 00:39:35.560
Quarrels and brawls of the most
violent description were frequent

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:37.510
consequences of these meetings.

00:39:37.510 --> 00:39:40.630
And whenever they became especially
dangerous and glasses were thrown,

00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:44.500
dirks drawn, and pistols fired, it
was the duty of the slaves to rush

00:39:44.500 --> 00:39:48.740
in and each one drag his master
from the fight and carry him home."

00:39:48.740 --> 00:39:51.130
So you can see what the
black people thought

00:39:51.130 --> 00:39:52.730
about the white people's
drinking habits.

00:39:52.730 --> 00:39:55.470
You know, when we go through
history, you can get bigotry

00:39:55.470 --> 00:39:58.820
on both sides, although
this sounds pretty accurate.

00:40:00.100 --> 00:40:03.650
Next is Hannah's daughter,
Nancy Hillman.

00:40:03.650 --> 00:40:07.960
Hannah had worked at a tavern
where lawyers frequented

00:40:07.960 --> 00:40:09.460
because it was close
to the courthouse,

00:40:09.460 --> 00:40:13.000
and I think that's why Nancy
is -- a detail in the book,

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:14.840
knew a lot about the law.

00:40:14.840 --> 00:40:18.900
But Nancy eventually moved --
Yarrow's niece, moved to Frederick,

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:22.740
Maryland, and married a
man who was the servant

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:25.860
or slave of Judge Richard Potts.

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:27.490
So it all makes sense, you know.

00:40:27.490 --> 00:40:31.100
She worked in a tavern, she knew
lawyers, so she would marry a man

00:40:31.100 --> 00:40:32.640
who would be her social equal.

00:40:32.640 --> 00:40:36.570
A man who was familiar with the
law, and that all made sense.

00:40:36.570 --> 00:40:40.630
And the Hillman family was a
pretty prominent black family

00:40:40.630 --> 00:40:42.010
in Frederick, Maryland.

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:45.170
And today, Frederick's a
small town, but in those days,

00:40:45.170 --> 00:40:48.350
it was sort of the legal capital of
the country because all the judges

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:51.000
and justices were coming
out of Frederick, Maryland,

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:56.210
including Chief Justice Roger Brook
Taney was a man from Frederick.

00:40:56.210 --> 00:41:00.260
And he knew Nancy Hillman,
and that's important.

00:41:00.260 --> 00:41:02.740
The Chief Justice of the United
States would have known the Hillman

00:41:02.740 --> 00:41:04.740
family and would have
known Nancy Hillman.

00:41:04.740 --> 00:41:06.940
And she was a pretty savvy woman.

00:41:06.940 --> 00:41:09.710
But Chief Justice Roger
Taney was also the man

00:41:09.710 --> 00:41:12.250
who wrote the decision
in Dred Scott.

00:41:12.250 --> 00:41:15.480
And as a story in race in America,
let's look at what this man,

00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:18.730
who knew Nancy Hillman,
said about black people.

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:21.060
"They, [African Americans]
had for more than a century,

00:41:21.060 --> 00:41:23.540
before the Constitution,
been regarded as being

00:41:23.540 --> 00:41:27.250
of an inferior order, and
altogether unfit to associate

00:41:27.250 --> 00:41:30.950
with the white race either in
social or political relations.

00:41:30.950 --> 00:41:33.690
And so far inferior
that they had no rights

00:41:33.690 --> 00:41:35.700
which the white man
was bound to respect.

00:41:35.700 --> 00:41:38.300
And the negro might justly
and lawfully be reduced

00:41:38.300 --> 00:41:40.130
to slavery for his benefit."

00:41:40.130 --> 00:41:42.180
This was the most racist
decision ever to come

00:41:42.180 --> 00:41:44.900
out of the Supreme Court.

00:41:44.900 --> 00:41:48.010
So racist that in the
north, there were calls

00:41:48.010 --> 00:41:50.170
to abolish the Supreme Court.

00:41:50.170 --> 00:41:53.910 position:56%
The view being if we have a Supreme
Court Chief Justice saying this kind

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:56.650
of stuff, we don't
need a Supreme Court.

00:41:56.650 --> 00:41:57.950
Now, why do I tell you this?

00:41:57.950 --> 00:41:59.540
Because it's a story
of race in America.

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:02.380
It's a man who would have
known the Yarrow family.

00:42:02.380 --> 00:42:06.510
He knew Nancy Hillman, and he
was saying this kind of garbage.

00:42:06.510 --> 00:42:10.780
But in my research, I went
up to Frederick, Maryland,

00:42:10.780 --> 00:42:13.320
because I knew Nancy
Hillman died and was buried,

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:16.900
and this is St. Paul, St.
John's Catholic Church

00:42:16.900 --> 00:42:18.200
in Frederick, Maryland.

00:42:18.200 --> 00:42:21.650
The cemetery, this tombstone
says "Hillman, Nanny Hillman."

00:42:21.650 --> 00:42:24.680
It's not Nancy, but it's
the Hillman section.

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:27.890
The sexton of the cemetery told
me this is the black section,

00:42:27.890 --> 00:42:30.700
Catholic Church's cemetery.

00:42:30.700 --> 00:42:34.310
And so I'm sure that Nancy
Hillman, Yarrow's daughter --

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:36.840
Yarrow's niece is buried here.

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:39.040
But if you look past
that obelisk there,

00:42:39.040 --> 00:42:40.980
all the way over to the
other side of the seminary,

00:42:40.980 --> 00:42:43.920
and go there like I did,
you come to the grave

00:42:43.920 --> 00:42:46.780
Of Chief Justice Roger Taney.

00:42:46.780 --> 00:42:49.580
He's buried in an integrated
cemetery.

00:42:49.580 --> 00:42:53.060
So, you know, you may be
a racist in your life,

00:42:53.060 --> 00:42:56.320
but you can never control what
might happen to you in eternity.

00:42:56.320 --> 00:43:00.240
You just should remember that.

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:01.540
Alright, so we're going on.

00:43:01.540 --> 00:43:03.730
I'm going to skip over
Aquilla Yarrow, Yarrow's son.

00:43:03.730 --> 00:43:06.300
A little bit, he died in 1832.

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:12.030
But I wanted to focus on his
wife, Mary Turner or Polly Yarrow.

00:43:12.030 --> 00:43:16.610
First of all, Samuel Bell was in
business with a man named Turner.

00:43:16.610 --> 00:43:18.020
And in fact, they lived --

00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:20.890
had adjacent plantations
in Montgomery County.

00:43:20.890 --> 00:43:25.540
And so I think Yarrow's son,
Aquilla, married Mary Turner,

00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:29.400
a slave of Samuel Turner.

00:43:29.400 --> 00:43:32.380
Samuel Turner died in 1809.

00:43:32.380 --> 00:43:36.210 position:56%
He was register of Wills, worked out
of the same courthouse as Bell did.

00:43:36.210 --> 00:43:40.840
This is, excuse me, his signing
as the Register of Wills here,

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:44.090
and the next will is his
because he has died in 1809.

00:43:44.090 --> 00:43:47.160 position:56%
So -- and he had a slave named Mary.

00:43:47.160 --> 00:43:52.900
I next see them up in
Washington County, up in 1832,

00:43:52.900 --> 00:43:56.200
and you see on the bottom right,
Mary Turner and Aquilla Yarrow.

00:43:56.200 --> 00:43:58.350
This is in a schedule
of free persons of color

00:43:58.350 --> 00:44:00.840
in Washington County, and
they're living together,

00:44:00.840 --> 00:44:02.790
actually as husband and wife.

00:44:02.790 --> 00:44:06.530
So you know, that's the connection,

00:44:06.530 --> 00:44:11.920
that Polly Yarrow is Yarrow
Mamout's daughter-in-law.

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:14.430
And then Aquilla died
right after this was done.

00:44:14.430 --> 00:44:15.730
He died in 1832.

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:21.260 position:56%
So I went and I got his inventory
of his estate and looked through it,

00:44:21.260 --> 00:44:26.860
and here is some of the things he
owned, including a lot of yarn.

00:44:26.860 --> 00:44:31.330
And you see in the margin, "Polly,"
meaning she owned that, not him.

00:44:31.330 --> 00:44:34.800
So I know that Polly and Aquilla
were living together as husband

00:44:34.800 --> 00:44:36.530
and wife in the same house.

00:44:36.530 --> 00:44:39.350
But one of the remarkable things

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:43.170
about this inventory
is the last line here,

00:44:43.170 --> 00:44:45.660
that you see a lot of books.

00:44:45.660 --> 00:44:50.230
There's a black man living in
the middle of nowhere in 1832,

00:44:50.230 --> 00:44:53.040
on a tiny little farm,
and he's got books.

00:44:53.040 --> 00:44:54.690
Why would he have books?

00:44:54.690 --> 00:44:56.290
Because he can read.

00:44:56.290 --> 00:45:00.270
Yarrow Mamout had arranged
for him to learn to read.

00:45:00.270 --> 00:45:03.640
Otherwise there would have been
no reason for a black man, anyone,

00:45:03.640 --> 00:45:05.320
to have books if you can't read.

00:45:05.320 --> 00:45:08.840
So I think that Yarrow made
sure that his son got educated.

00:45:08.840 --> 00:45:12.230
But I was telling Ellen
this before my talk,

00:45:12.230 --> 00:45:15.300
and I said that at some point,
you know, I do like libraries.

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:16.720
And I do like archives.

00:45:16.720 --> 00:45:19.400
It's a little tedious
to spend all day in a --

00:45:19.400 --> 00:45:22.110
but sometimes you've
just got to get out.

00:45:22.110 --> 00:45:24.070
And that happens even
in my research.

00:45:24.070 --> 00:45:27.140
So I thought, "You know,
I've just got to get out."

00:45:27.140 --> 00:45:31.060
My story was sort of coming to a
dead end, and so I thought, "Well,

00:45:31.060 --> 00:45:34.240
I'm going to go up to Antietam
and see what's up there."

00:45:34.240 --> 00:45:35.830
And when I did -- now
this is actually true.

00:45:35.830 --> 00:45:37.290
I'm not making this up.

00:45:37.290 --> 00:45:41.490
When I decided to go up to Antietam
to actually look at the ground,

00:45:41.490 --> 00:45:47.490
I was looking at a map, and
I saw this: Yarrowsburg Road.

00:45:47.490 --> 00:45:52.580
I had no idea there
was a Yarrowsburg Road,

00:45:52.580 --> 00:45:57.070
nor did I have any idea as to
why there was a Yarrowsburg Road.

00:45:57.070 --> 00:45:59.190
I would not have found
this in a library

00:45:59.190 --> 00:46:02.240
or book except by looking at a map.

00:46:02.240 --> 00:46:04.470
So I went in there, and this
is downtown Yarrowsburg,

00:46:04.470 --> 00:46:05.780
there's nothing there.

00:46:05.780 --> 00:46:09.570
But there were two men talking
over to the side of the road,

00:46:09.570 --> 00:46:11.270
so I went up to them, and I said,

00:46:11.270 --> 00:46:13.730
"Can you tell me why this
place is named Yarrowsburg?"

00:46:13.730 --> 00:46:16.590
And the one man, Bill
[inaudible] said, "Yes!

00:46:16.590 --> 00:46:20.810
My grandfather told me it was named
after a woman named Polly Yarrow."

00:46:20.810 --> 00:46:23.590
And you know, that
Polly in the margin

00:46:23.590 --> 00:46:25.980
of that was just sticking
in my head.

00:46:25.980 --> 00:46:29.170
But I'm a lawyer, and so
you don't lead witnesses.

00:46:29.170 --> 00:46:32.660
And you don't get good research if
you give them the answers you want.

00:46:32.660 --> 00:46:35.850
So I just waited him
out because I knew

00:46:35.850 --> 00:46:38.020
that he wanted to say
something else.

00:46:38.020 --> 00:46:39.320
And I just waited him out.

00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:43.380 position:56%
And finally, after about 15 seconds,
he said, "She was black, you know."

00:46:43.380 --> 00:46:45.870 position:56%
And that's what I wanted him to say.

00:46:45.870 --> 00:46:47.510
And he said, "She was
the midwife here.

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:48.900
Delivered all the babies,
black and white.

00:46:48.900 --> 00:46:51.800
My grandfather told me that's
why this is Yarrowsburg."

00:46:51.800 --> 00:46:56.510
And so that added this whole
new dimension to this story.

00:46:56.510 --> 00:46:58.960
That hill in the background
is called Elk Ridge.

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:00.730
The locals call it "the mountain."

00:47:00.730 --> 00:47:04.450
But if you go over that, as I did,
on foot -- there used to be a road,

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:07.940
but if you go over it on foot, on
the other side, you come down here

00:47:07.940 --> 00:47:12.210 position:56%
to the Kennedy Farm, and many people
don't know what the Kennedy Farm is.

00:47:12.210 --> 00:47:16.420
But you will because that's
where John Brown and 22 men holed

00:47:16.420 --> 00:47:18.190
up before the raid
on Harper's Ferry.

00:47:18.190 --> 00:47:19.810
They were there for three months.

00:47:19.810 --> 00:47:24.170
So I think that Polly Yarrow
probably knew that John Brown --

00:47:24.170 --> 00:47:27.760
knew that there was something
going on there at the Kennedy Farm

00:47:27.760 --> 00:47:29.510
because it was only a
mile from her house.

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:30.810
And she was the midwife,

00:47:30.810 --> 00:47:32.440
and midwives did more
than deliver babies.

00:47:32.440 --> 00:47:34.900
They were sort of first-echelon
nurses.

00:47:34.900 --> 00:47:37.930
And so they may have called on her.

00:47:40.340 --> 00:47:42.990
We move from Polly -- I'm
going to come back to Polly,

00:47:42.990 --> 00:47:46.290
but to her nephew, Simon Turner.

00:47:46.290 --> 00:47:50.150 position:56%
He was born here in a springhouse
or slave cabin on the Crampton Farm,

00:47:50.150 --> 00:47:53.530
near Crampton's Gap,
near Yarrowsburg.

00:47:53.530 --> 00:47:58.140
And then the story starts getting
better because I get better records

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:03.540
because in 1864, Simon
Turner joined the Union army.

00:48:03.540 --> 00:48:07.730
And his wife later applied for a
pension and said this about it:

00:48:07.730 --> 00:48:09.810
"My husband Simon Turner
and I were both slaves

00:48:09.810 --> 00:48:11.110
at the time we were married.

00:48:11.110 --> 00:48:15.210 position:56%
My husband belonged to Eli Crampton,
and I belonged to Mr. John Gray.

00:48:15.210 --> 00:48:17.290
Both our masters in
slavery are dead.

00:48:17.290 --> 00:48:19.350
They were coming around
drafting men,

00:48:19.350 --> 00:48:23.500
and he [Simon] said he wanted not
to be drafted, and so he enlisted.

00:48:23.500 --> 00:48:27.550
I did not see my husband from the
time he enlisted in March 1864

00:48:27.550 --> 00:48:32.330
until he came home
in August of 1865."

00:48:32.330 --> 00:48:35.290
There's only one picture
of the unit he joined,

00:48:35.290 --> 00:48:37.280
The 39th Regiment U.S. Color Troop.

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:38.650
This is that picture.

00:48:38.650 --> 00:48:41.000
Naturally the white
officers are in the front,

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:44.130
but there are troopers in the back.

00:48:44.130 --> 00:48:48.660 position:56%
When I showed the Turner family this
photograph, they looked at the tall,

00:48:48.660 --> 00:48:50.900
skinny black man in the
background, and they said,

00:48:50.900 --> 00:48:53.270
"That looks like Uncle Mark."

00:48:53.270 --> 00:48:57.480
He does. I saw a picture of
Uncle Mark, but I can't be sure.

00:48:57.480 --> 00:49:00.070
Anyhow, I may have a
picture of Simon Turner.

00:49:00.070 --> 00:49:06.660
After the war, he settled here
in Pleasant Valley, Maryland.

00:49:06.660 --> 00:49:10.360
And up at the top of this
picture, it's hard for you to see,

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:13.770
but there's marked,
"Mrs. Yarrow's house."

00:49:13.770 --> 00:49:18.760
She was famous enough for her
house to be marked on an 1877 map.

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:23.600
And Simon Turner was living with
his father-in-law, Arthur Sands,

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:26.540
who's marked on the map, and it's
only about a half a mile apart.

00:49:26.540 --> 00:49:28.010
So they knew each other.

00:49:28.010 --> 00:49:30.820
And then Polly died.

00:49:30.820 --> 00:49:32.660
"An old colored woman
named Polly Yarrow,

00:49:32.660 --> 00:49:35.780
whose exact age was not
known, but was over 100 years,

00:49:35.780 --> 00:49:38.620
died on last Saturday in the little
village called Yarrowsburg near

00:49:38.620 --> 00:49:42.320
Crampton's Gap and Pleasant
Valley in this county."

00:49:42.320 --> 00:49:44.130
Second black person in this family

00:49:44.130 --> 00:49:46.940
to have an obituary
in a white newspaper.

00:49:46.940 --> 00:49:50.710
These people, this was
in a period of slavery.

00:49:50.710 --> 00:49:54.910
These people were so talented
that they are being recognized,

00:49:54.910 --> 00:49:58.970
albeit at their death, with
obituaries in white newspapers.

00:50:01.430 --> 00:50:06.160
And nearing the end, we have
Simon's daughter, Emma Turner.

00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:07.500
I don't deal with all the family,

00:50:07.500 --> 00:50:10.580
only Emma because she
was a very bright girl,

00:50:10.580 --> 00:50:16.650
and she grew up in Pleasant
Valley and then went to college

00:50:16.650 --> 00:50:18.410
over here in Harper's Ferry.

00:50:18.410 --> 00:50:20.960
That's Harper's Ferry,
where John Brown was.

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:24.520
And [inaudible] College, and
she got a degree in education.

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:29.550 position:56%
The first one in her family to get a
college degree, at least in America.

00:50:29.550 --> 00:50:32.540
And she married a man from
Howard named Robert Ford,

00:50:32.540 --> 00:50:34.290
who was a divinity student.

00:50:34.290 --> 00:50:36.600
And they moved around
a lot, but ultimately,

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:38.440
they settled in Baltimore.

00:50:38.440 --> 00:50:40.880
And here's Emma.

00:50:40.880 --> 00:50:44.030
She dies in 1956, so
I've got a picture.

00:50:44.030 --> 00:50:47.340
This woman, by the
way, knew Polly Yarrow.

00:50:47.340 --> 00:50:50.880
She knew Yarrow Mamout's
daughter-in-law

00:50:50.880 --> 00:50:53.500
because she was ten years old when
Polly died, and she was living

00:50:53.500 --> 00:50:56.150
in that -- a half-mile away.

00:50:56.150 --> 00:51:01.640
Anyway, they had a son, and one
of their sons, Robert Turner Ford.

00:51:01.640 --> 00:51:09.370
And in 1923, Robert Turner
Ford, her son, went to Harvard.

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:13.460
You know, it was a different
Harvard then than it was today.

00:51:13.460 --> 00:51:15.130
There wasn't Affirmative Action.

00:51:15.130 --> 00:51:17.110
Blacks had to be ten
times more talented

00:51:17.110 --> 00:51:18.980
than white people to
get into Harvard.

00:51:18.980 --> 00:51:22.560
And in 1984, this man
went back to Harvard

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:25.870 position:56%
and described what it was like then.

00:51:25.870 --> 00:51:28.610
There were only seven other
blacks that -- six other blacks.

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:30.690
"In the black segment of
the segregated society

00:51:30.690 --> 00:51:33.450
in which I was born and
bred, there was an almost --

00:51:33.450 --> 00:51:35.870
almost [inaudible] faith
in education as a means

00:51:35.870 --> 00:51:38.840
of attaining social worth
and economic freedom.

00:51:38.840 --> 00:51:41.930
College graduates were
rare in that society."

00:51:41.930 --> 00:51:45.870
His grandfather and three of
his uncles had been slaves.

00:51:45.870 --> 00:51:47.830
And he's saying college
graduates are rare.

00:51:47.830 --> 00:51:49.420
And they were illiterate.

00:51:49.420 --> 00:51:52.710
"College graduates were rare,
and the possession of a diploma

00:51:52.710 --> 00:51:55.900
of any kind identified one as being
a member of an elite group entitled

00:51:55.900 --> 00:51:57.280
in leadership and respect.

00:51:57.280 --> 00:51:59.410
A graduate of Harvard
with all of its traditions

00:51:59.410 --> 00:52:01.130
and history was viewed
as the epitome

00:52:01.130 --> 00:52:03.010
of academic and social merit."

00:52:03.010 --> 00:52:05.950
This is by a man, again, whose --

00:52:05.950 --> 00:52:08.360
came out of slavery
and went to Harvard.

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:11.240
Graduated in 1927.

00:52:11.240 --> 00:52:13.080
My research took me to Yarrowsburg.

00:52:13.080 --> 00:52:15.590
This is Mt. Moriah
Baptist Church there,

00:52:15.590 --> 00:52:18.240
and in the cemetery is
the grave of Simon Turner.

00:52:18.240 --> 00:52:21.070
It says, "He died to
save the Union."

